The Real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses.
I grew up with it.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were expelled from their southern bases by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Harassed and persecuted by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and rugged grasslands, with Mao steering the column from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against incredibly poor prospects, the Red Armies reached northwest China.
Only one fifth of the original 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they returned victorious, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
In what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to follow its trail.
It is still a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I found 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or managed to make it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was barely taller than his rifle when he joined the Red Army as a child.
He had no choice: His father was detained and not released until Huang agreed.
He thought about fleeing the country, but remained out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many fled.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
But no more than 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, fought at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. According to legend, 22 brave men overpowered a regiment of nationalist troops that guarded the Luding Bridge with machine guns, thus clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event of the entire Long March, and it is still celebrated as such today.
But documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu first told party historians a completely different story. "The matter wasn't as complicated as people later portrayed it," he said. "When studying historical facts, one should stick to the truth."
How it is portrayed is another issue."
So lives the legend on.
Only a minor dispute was heard above Dadu.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
In return, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The marchers did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the final goal.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
Den Frauen wurde befohlen, umzudrehen und nach Hause zurückzukehren, weil es nicht genug Essen gab.
Knapp einen Monat nach der Vereinigung der drei Roten Armeen beschloss die Partei, dass der Lange Marsch weitergehen musste.
Doch rettete sie die Entführung Chiang Kai-sheks durch den General, den Chiang eingesetzt hatte, um die Kommunisten zu vernichten.
Als Teil des Preises für seine Freilassung erkannte Chiang die Kommunisten als rechtmäßig an.
Der Lange Marsch war beendet.
Not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion, however.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, which was led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's main rival, and their mission was to cross the western Chinese border to seek help from Russia.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Surrounded on barren land where survival was difficult, they were annihilated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 made it to the border; the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, she is missing from the official historical narrative.
A Muslim commander took Wang Quanyan, the leading officer, as his mistress.
This was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despairing, and persevered.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom money.
The purges continued until practically no officers remained to take command in battles.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice that is unparalleled in the history of China and other nations.

What drove her to do it?
I questioned one of the top generals about what he knew about communism back then. "I didn't know then, and I don't know now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, a hope for a just and progressive society.
No one might have known – or could have known – how much suffering was yet to come, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the gap between the dream and reality would be.
